# Global Audit Memory

## Scope Touched
- `contracts/proxy/AdminUpgradeabilityProxy.sol`: primary focus; admin lifecycle, constructor ordering, `upgradeToAndCall`, and zero-admin edge cases repeatedly mattered
- `contracts/proxy/UpgradeabilityProxy.sol`: implementation-slot and upgrade flow behavior stayed central, especially initializer delegatecalls and code-presence assumptions
- `contracts/proxy/Proxy.sol`: fallback/delegation semantics remained relevant, including behavior when the implementation address later has no code
- `@openzeppelin/contracts/utils/Address.sol`: reviewed around `isContract` and `sendValue`, but no durable issue direction survived
- `0x7fbd6b0e72588751f7ffc25e8df2612c2655be77/Contract.sol`: touched once without follow-through; underexplored relative to proxy-heavy attention

## Issue Directions Seen
- Proxy constructor-time initialization order can let privileged roles be captured before transparent-proxy admin state is fully established
- `upgradeToAndCall` creates recurring risk around role assignment and transparent-admin usability mismatches
- Admin-path misconfiguration is a durable theme, especially zero-admin setups that brick upgrade and recovery capabilities
- Delegatecall-based initialization/upgrade flows are the main risk surface, but only concrete lifecycle-specific manifestations have held up
- Implementation liveness assumptions matter: the proxy may keep delegating to an address whose code disappears, turning calls into silent no-ops

## Useful Context
- Cross-round attention is concentrated on the proxy stack; most durable observations come from proxy lifecycle behavior rather than generic library risks
- The strongest patterns are concrete state-machine and role-routing issues, not abstract “delegatecall is dangerous” claims
- `Address.sol` and broader OpenZeppelin utility concerns were explored but have not produced retained findings so far
- A recurring distinction is between who receives a role during initialization/upgrade and who can actually exercise that role through a transparent proxy

